05466nam a22007935i 9780801458491DE-B159720220302035458.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220302t20112011nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a97808014584917 a10.7591/97808014584912doi  a(DE-B1597)478676  a(OCoLC)979577006  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aHD8066b.D42 2009 7aPOL0130002bisacsh04a331.8809732221 aDean, Amy B., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut12aA New New Deal :bHow Regional Activism Will Reshape the American Labor Movement /cDavid B. Reynolds, Amy B. Dean. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2011] 4c©2011  a1 online resource (304 p.) :b1 line figure  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aA Century Foundation Book00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tForeword by Harold Meyerson -- tA Note from The Century Foundation by Richard C. Leone -- tPreface -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction -- tThe Birth of Regional Power Building -- t1. Thinking Regionally -- t2. The Regional Power-Building Model Emerges in California -- tThe Three Legs of Regional Power Building -- t3. Developing a Regional Policy Agenda -- t4. Deep Coalitions -- t5. From Access to Governance: Building Aggressive Political Action -- tThe Spread of Regional Power Building -- t6. Understanding the Spread of Regional Power Building across the Country -- t7. Toward a National Strategy for Spreading Regional Power Building -- tNotes -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aIn A New New Deal, the labor movement leaders Amy B. Dean and David B. Reynolds offer a bold new plan to revitalize American labor activism and build a sense of common purpose between labor and community organizations. Dean and Reynolds demonstrate how alliances organized at the regional level are the most effective tool to build a voice for working people in the workplace, community, and halls of government.The authors draw on their own successes to offer in-depth, contemporary case studies of effective labor-community coalitions. They also outline a concrete strategy for building power at the regional level. This pioneering model presents the regional building blocks for national change. A diverse audience—both within the labor movement and among its allies—will welcome this clear, detailed, and inspiring presentation of regional power-building tactics, which include deep coalition-building, leadership development, policy research, and aggressive political action.A New New Deal explores successful coalitions forged in Los Angeles, Boston, Denver, San Jose, New Haven, and Atlanta toward goals such as universal health insurance for children and sensible redevelopment efforts that benefit workers as well as businesses. The authors view partnerships between labor and grassroots organizations as a mutually beneficial strategy based on shared goals, resulting in a broadened membership base and increased organizational capacity. They make the innovative argument that the labor movement can steward both industry and community and make manifest the ways in which workplace battles are not the parochial concerns of isolated workers, but a fundamental struggle for America's future.Drawing on historical parallels, the authors illustrate how long-term collaborations between labor and community organizations are sowing the seeds of a new New Deal.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 02. Mrz 2022) 0aCoalitionszUnited States. 0aCommunity developmentzUnited States. 0aLabor movementzUnited States. 0aRegionalismzUnited States. 0aWorking classzUnited States. 4aLabor History. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 4aUrban Studies. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Labor & Industrial Relations.2bisacsh1 aMeyerson, Harold.1 aReynolds, David B., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080145849140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801458491423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780801458491/original  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aEBA_STMALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA12STME  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK